  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_666351063" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/666351063" />
    <a title="Tim" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/108788-tim"><img alt="Tim" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1442498661p2/108788.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/666351063?book_show_action=true">Jul 12, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tim" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tim" href="/user/show/108788-tim">Tim</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer666351063" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18369787477387647121">Recommended by Dawn Tripp.<br/><br/>When I was in high school, I had the privilege of having one of those English teachers that you&apos;d feel damned lucky to run across in the pages of a book, much less in real life. Morrow Jones would shape me indelibly as a reader, a writer, a film buff, a teacher, and a person. One of the many projects we took on together was that of creating fiction in unusual forms and shapes--a t shirt, a set of fake Cliff&apos;s Notes for a nonexistent book, and a story on a möbius strip. </span>
  <span id="freeText18369787477387647121" style="display:none">Recommended by Dawn Tripp.<br /><br />When I was in high school, I had the privilege of having one of those English teachers that you'd feel damned lucky to run across in the pages of a book, much less in real life. Morrow Jones would shape me indelibly as a reader, a writer, a film buff, a teacher, and a person. One of the many projects we took on together was that of creating fiction in unusual forms and shapes--a t shirt, a set of fake Cliff's Notes for a nonexistent book, and a story on a möbius strip. It's the last of these that springs to mind as I try to wrap my mind around <i>Embers</i>, for the book itself seems to twist and coil even as one is reading it. Unlike some books which culminate in a revelation (I'm thinking here of Julian Barnes's <i>The Sense of an Ending</i> as a prominent recent example), the surprise turn of events that unfolds in this book seems almost anticlimactic, as though its very purpose is to nudge one back toward the subtler twists and turns that accompanied one every step of the way. Nabokov made a strong case that every reading is a rereading, but nah, not really, not exactly. This one, though, has no qualms about grabbing you by the collar and pretty much insisting <i> get back there, page one, prestissimo!</i> If it weren't such a flagrant crime against the environment, I'd say its pages ought to repeat themselves a second time.<br /><br />Like Barnes’s novel, <i>Embers</i> is a slow build that rises to a steady boil, a set of gestures and echoes, feints and intimations that amount to more than the mere page count would suggest. Near the opening, Márai describes how in memory, “time…fades things to the colorlessness of ancient photographs fixed on metal plates. Light and time erase the contours and distinctive shading of the faces. One has to angle the image this way and that until it catches the light in a particular way and one can make out the person whose feature have been absorbed into the blank surface of the plate…But then one day light strikes from a certain angle and one recaptures a face again.” This might be a fractal image of the novel as a whole, which reveals its characters from many angles, some of them partial and hazy, others sharp and incontrovertible. In tracing the friendship and then parting of ways between the General, Henrik, who grows up in a nearly calcifying privilege and wealth, and Konrad, the musician who is raised in abject poverty, Márai is able to explore many themes: the nature of friendship first and foremost, its delicate alchemy of likeness and dissimilarity, along with its uncertain relation to eros and sexual love. But there's much else: the distinction between facts and so-called "truth," the degree to which order can arrange one's world and life, and the anarchic, Dionysian, soul-shaking power of music. Márai treats this last in a manner that begs comparison to Tolstoy's in <i>The Kreutzer Sonata</i>--as something sufficiently dangerous as to threaten morality itself, even as it "demand[s]...that people be themselves in heart and mind." <br /><br />As for its own musicality, in Carol Brown Janeway's translation, <i>Embers</i> advances with a quieter music, not that which "required brass, and a drum major to march in front and throw his silver staff periodically into the air," nor the Chopin that nearly causes furniture to levitate at one point. I suppose the term "quiet novel" gets overused (as for mine, they all murmur and occasionally thrum, guns-ablazing thrillers barely louder than the introspective consciousness-benders). But this novel invites it in that quiet itself is so richly, melodiously captured: "The two men are speaking in hushed tones and yet their voices echo: like stringed instruments, the ancient wooden panels covering the walls also vibrate to the muffled words, amplifying them." <br /><br />It's such echoes, and of course the figurative ones even more, that make <i>Embers</i> such a prime candidate for rereading. There is no word in the English language, insofar as I know, for the initial sound that causes echoes, the sonic flint that sets them off. I'd propose "narcissus," except that that domain name's already taken in a big way. My point is that on the second go-around, everything becomes louder in this book, from the impact of Konrad's impoverished upbringing to the early hints of the complex relationship between Henrik and Nini, his nurse. It is a book that teaches one how better to listen--to it and in general--that attunes one and resounds accordingly. If I could figure out a way to publish this review on a möbius strip, I would. <br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /> <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="18369787477387647121" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


